Berg told the Post that MK David Rotem (Yisrael Beytenu), who brought the bill to a vote, agrees with these assessments. "This is the first meaningful campaign reform in many years," said Rotem.

Rotem stressed that bringing international observers would give an international stamp of approval to Israel's electoral system, and that moving up the voting date to outside the Passover holiday would make it more convenient for ultra-Orthodox voters, and that postponing voting to after the second day of Shavuot was "not realistic" because "the holiday already starts before sunset and [voters] have to remain outside the polling stations."
